Subject: [MSN] US. Theft of 200-year-old whaling harpoons a baffling
	case, FBI joins investigation of maritime instruments missing from
	Cape May County Museum
To: Museum Security Network Mailinglist <msn-list@te.verweg.com>
Message-ID: <4684FFE1.1070006@bruggemansolutions.com>
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8; format=flowed

Theft of 200-year-old whaling harpoons a baffling case
FBI joins investigation of maritime instruments missing from Cape May County Museum
By BRIAN IANIERI Staff Writer, (609) 463-6713
Published: Tuesday, June 26, 2007
MIDDLE TOWNSHIP ? Call me Agent Ishmael.

The FBI has been called in to help township officials solve the case of the missing whaling harpoons.

It's an odd crime that took place at the Cape May County Museum three weeks ago, involving the disappearance of various whaling implements used in the early 19th century.

Township police and the FBI's Art Theft Program are investigating the theft of six whaling harpoons, a whaling gun and several other maritime instruments, police Capt. Scott Webster said Monday.

Authorities have been monitoring online auction sites in case the 200-year-old harpoons make an appearance, Webster said.

?It's an ongoing investigation,? Webster said. ?The FBI has a division that does a lot of background on art thefts and that type of theft, and we've been dealing with them.?

Not surprisingly, the harpoon thefts do not place on the FBI's ?Top Ten Art Crimes,? as listed on their Web site.

Nor does it rank alongside the millions of dollars worth of stolen Norman Rockwells and Claude Monets.

But the harpoon thefts has been somewhat baffling, if but for one simple question: Who in the world would steal heavy, pointy pieces of metal that may or may not have been inside a whale?

Museum officials have said they believe the culprit was a collector and someone who knows his harpoons. Only six were stolen from a glass museum case that contained other harpoons, bone spades, blubber pikes and another harpoon gun.

Three sailor's palm thimbles ? used in sail making ? and a sextant also were stolen from the maritime exhibit.

The exhibit is located in a locked barn, and museum workers believe someone unlocked the doors from the inside before returning later in the day or night.

A museum worker noticed the missing items the morning of June 5 while plugging in the lighted display.

The county museum is by no means a hotbed of crime. Officials could recall only a few instances of anything being stolen there.

In one case about two decades ago, someone attempted to steal old arrowheads in a glass casing from the museum, said Somers Corson, a former museum curator.

But a resident of a nearby nursing home noticed the burglary, and the arrowheads were recovered quickly, Corson said.

?I'd almost forgotten about that until the harpoons were stolen,? Corson said. ?It's just somebody looking for financial value is all, or else they're a real enthusiastic collector. Of course, it's hard to tell ?someone must have known what they wanted, because they were the best ones they took.?

Anyone with information about the missing harpoons should contact Middle Township police at (609) 465-8700 or anonymously to Cape May County Crime Stoppers at (609) 465-2800.

http://www.pressofatlanticcity.com




