06/26/2007 06:39:56 AM MDT

SANTA FE ? A Santa Fe businessman sentenced to 34 years in prison for deceiving people who invested thousands of dollars in a defunct capital city art market could face more prison time.

The state attorney general's office has filed additional information alleging that Michael Soutar was convicted of assault in Bernalillo County in 1991 and forgery in Maricopa County, Ariz., in 1997.

Soutar, 48, admitted to the convictions Monday in state district court.

It's unclear if the convictions mean Soutar will face an extra two years or eight years, said his attorney, Dan Cron.

Soutar's sentencing is scheduled for July 9.

State District Judge Michael Vigil had sentenced Soutar in May after he determined that Soutar could not pay up to $200,000 in restitution that had been agreed upon as part of a plea deal several months earlier.

Vigil sentenced Soutar to nine years for racketeering and another nine years on counts of securities fraud. He added 16 years to Soutar's term for being a habitual criminal.

