Message: 17
Date: Fri, 29 Jun 2007 14:49:44 +0200
From: Museum Security Network Mailing list <msn-list@te.verweg.com>
Subject: [MSN] No guarantee Japanese art safe in diplomatic missions
To: Museum Security Network Mailinglist <msn-list@te.verweg.com>
Message-ID: <4684FFE8.5050808@bruggemansolutions.com>
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8; format=flowed

No guarantee Japanese art safe in diplomatic missions
06/26/2007
THE ASAHI SHIMBUN

Dozens of valuable art works hanging at Japanese embassies and other Foreign Ministry missions overseas have been thrown out with the garbage or lost, according to officials.

In total, 46 works of art have disappeared since 2002, the Foreign Ministry said, citing a survey it conducted in response to requests for information by Yukichi Maeda, a Lower House member of Minshuto (Democratic Party of Japan), and Muneo Suzuki, a Lower House member of New Party Daichi.

The finding sparked anger among Japanese artists who sold the works at discount prices or donated them in the expectation that the Foreign Ministry would take good care of them.

The artists were clearly honored that their works would be displayed at Japanese diplomatic missions abroad and had hoped the pictures and other works would contribute to greater understanding of Japan's culture.

Ministry officials said the art works in question were thrown away or disappeared because they were damaged beyond repair. Officials contended that the paintings were stored appropriately in all cases.

Twenty-nine of the paintings were created in the Showa Era (1926-1989). The others were copies of works by old masters, such as Taikan Yokoyama and Gyokudo Kawai.

Eleven of the 29 Showa Era works were Japanese-style paintings while six were done on ceramic ware.

The others included four Western-style paintings, four prints and two pieces of calligraphy.

Of those 29 art works, five were donated while eight were purchased for about 1.16 million yen in total between the 1950s and 1980s. The individual purchase price ranged from 8,000 yen to 400,000 yen.

Officials said no records existed of when the Foreign Ministry purchased the remaining 16 items, nor how much it paid for them.

The one item that inexplicably vanished is a Japanese-style painting titled "Ushio no Mai" (Dance of waves) by Kotaro Doi in Morioka.

The Foreign Ministry purchased the work in 1992 for 580,000 yen.

The painting went missing around April 2006 when it was displayed at the Japanese Embassy in Uzbekistan.

The embassy notified local authorities about a possible theft but the item was never recovered.

The painter, Doi, voiced his anger at the ministry's sloppiness.

"I had absolutely trusted the Foreign Ministry when I sold it, feeling as if I had parted with my own child," Doi said. "I felt honored (that the ministry had selected my work) and I sold it at about one-tenth of the price I would normally have charged."

A bereaved family member of a late Japanese calligrapher also expressed anger that the work donated to the Foreign Ministry in the 1980s had been lost.

"It is an insult," the family member said.

"(Calligraphy items) will not easily deteriorate if appropriately stored. I can't believe the explanation that it was discarded (because its condition had deteriorated)."

According to the Foreign Ministry, Japanese embassies, consulates-general and other overseas diplomatic missions have in excess of 4,000 items of art.

An official of the ministry's Overseas Establishments Division said the ministry had instructed its overseas missions to pay careful attention to temperature and humidity control in managing works of art.

"The items were thrown out because they had deteriorated to a point beyond repair, through mold and other stains," the official said.(IHT/Asahi: June 26,2007) 

http://www.asahi.com




