Message: 19
Date: Fri, 29 Jun 2007 14:49:04 +0200
From: Museum Security Network Mailing list <msn-list@te.verweg.com>
Subject: [MSN] US. Reviving faded history, Archivists, librarians get
	help to save withering documents
To: Museum Security Network Mailinglist <msn-list@te.verweg.com>
Message-ID: <4684FFC0.6080404@bruggemansolutions.com>
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8; format=flowed

Reviving faded history
Archivists, librarians get help to save withering documents

By BO EMERSON
The Atlanta Journal-Constitution
Published on: 06/28/07

The caller on the phone did not identify himself, but Augusta historians call him "Deep Throat."

Have a van outside the courthouse at a certain hour, the caller said. Be prepared to load up several garbage bags full of documents.

In fact, the cache of historic records would eventually fill 40 to 50 boxes, and would include pre-Revolutionary War papers, some of them autographed by signers of the Declaration of Independence.

Because someone with connections didn't want to see those documents go into a landfill, the Augusta Genealogical Society received an anonymous tip.

If their contact had not placed a call, Button Gwinnett's signature, and others, would have been trashed, said Thomas Dirksen, Augusta historian, and past president of the society. "Those records would have disappeared, and no one would have thought twice," he said.

Records vanish. They are stolen, lost, thrown away or simply stored out of sight and out of mind. They're eaten by moths, dust, mold, insects and mice. In Georgia, the humidity turns improperly stored papers to mush.

This week archivists, librarians and curators from Georgia and around the country are gathering at the Smithsonian Institutions in Washington, D.C., to learn how to keep local history from slipping through their hands.

Organized by the nonprofit group Heritage Preservation and the Institute of Museum and Library Sciences, the summit is a response to a discouraging survey conducted recently that demonstrated how fast America's historic archives are disintegrating. According to the survey:

? More than half of the country's 30,000 libraries, museums and archives have had articles that were damaged by moisture.

? 26 percent of collecting institutions have no environmental controls, including 40 percent of libraries.

? 80 percent of collections have no disaster plan.

The lack of such emergency plans came into focus after Hurricane Katrina. "I saw historical societies completely wiped out," said David Carmicheal, director of the Georgia Archives, who visited Mississippi after the flood. "Those places will never really recover a sense of their history."

But everyday disasters may do the most damage.

Moldy and crumbling

Some maps from Georgia's gold rush days were stored in the glorified closet that's called the archives room at the Lumpkin County Library, until an air conditioner concealed above the acoustic tile ceiling began leaking.

On a recent muggy Friday in picturesque Dahlonega, information specialist Debra Capponi opened the door of the tiny storage room at the library and gestured to the boxes, documents, maps, scrapbooks and bound volumes stacked in every corner. "It's looking good, believe it or not, compared to what we had before," she said.

Capponi showed the stained and curled maps, portions rendered illegible by damage from dripping water. While the leak has been fixed and the moldy ceiling tile replaced, the maps need restoring, which neither Capponi nor anyone else at the library is trained to do.

Capponi will learn about restoration at the summit in Washington. More important, she'll learn about applying for grants, organizing volunteers and developing emergency plans. Besides, when it comes to restoration, even more serious problems are at hand in Lumpkin County.

In another box are ledgers from a general store in Auraria, the boom town that popped up after gold was discovered in the Georgia mountains in 1828. A writer, in a loose, handsome script, records 1897 sales ? of coffee, eggs, butter, a hoe ? and notes payments (in the form of bags of gold.)

Some of these ledgers, and others from the sheriff's department recording crimes from the 1880s and 1890s, are crumbling, the leather covers chewed by either animals or time, the pages a riot of colorful molds.

Elsewhere are scrapbooks from the 1950s, many of them prepared by tireless Dahlonega booster Madeleine K. Anthony. They document everyday life in the mountain town and helped convince state and federal officials of the town's historic significance. Unfortunately they were glued together with some corrosive compound and are also fading, while emitting a sharp smell of vinegar.

"We're going to lose a lot of this," said Capponi.

Saved from trash bin

That Lumpkin County has so much to lose is due in large part to the redoubtable Anthony, who saved records from becoming trash when the old courthouse was turned into the Gold Museum. She stored documents in her house for 20 years, while barnstorming to raise funds for a new library.

"I think her beds were a little higher than usual for all the boxes stored underneath," said Sallie Sorahan, a Dahlonega retiree and volunteer, who catalogued the Anthony collection, which came to the new Lumpkin County Library after it was built in 1983. Anthony passed away in 1989.

Not every county has a Madeleine K. Anthony. In LaGrange, courthouse records dating to the founding of the county were stored in an unheated outbuilding at the Troup County jail. "I'm thinking it was a garden shed," said archivist Kaye Minchew. "Archivists in Georgia love to talk about how 'my cockroaches are bigger than your cockroaches,' but I'm sure theirs were big enough."

Luckily, historians and county officials came together, and, with the help of the Callaway foundation, created the Troup County Archives in a historic bank building, which now has about 12 million pages of records.

Minchew, director of the archives, is also attending the summit, and plans to seek new ideas for funding sources.

Anne-Imelda Radice, director of the Institute of Museum and Library Services, said the news from the survey is depressing, but the result of the study has been positive. "It has galvanized us," she said. "We've got a call to save our collections."

http://www.ajc.com/




